From: aorus-5090-egpu <noreply@example.invalid>
Date: Wed, 6 May 2026 14:55:00 +1000
Subject: [PATCH] Lever M-recover: probe-time WPR2-stuck detection (Commit 2)

Adds probe-time WPR2-stuck detection to the in-driver recovery state
machine scaffolding from patch 0016 (Commit 1). This is Commit 2 of 3
in the Lever M-recover series.

Detection-only in this commit. No recovery action; probe continues
normally. The existing failure path (rm_init_adapter fails on first
nv_start_device, aorus-egpu-wpr2-recovery.service performs L4 recovery
via dmesg-pattern detection) is unchanged.

Mechanism:
  - In nv_pci_probe, after BAR0 cpu_address is captured, do a temporary
    ioremap of one page covering BAR0 + 0x88a828
    (NV_HUBMMU0_PRI_BASE + NV_HUBMMU_PRI_MMU_WPR2_ADDR_HI on Blackwell
    GB100/GB202 per published headers).
  - Read 32-bit register, mask bits [31:4]. Non-zero ⇒ WPR2 is stuck up
    from a previous boot cycle and GSP boot will fail later.
  - On detection: increment fire_count, log NV_DBG_ERRORS marker, return.
    Probe continues normally.
  - iounmap before returning. No persistent mapping.

Why detection-only this commit:
  Recovery action requires careful PCI lifecycle (remove + rescan + reset)
  with refcount management across nvl-free, which has higher risk than
  probe-time detection. Staging detection first gives us real-world
  fire-rate data via the existing sysfs counter (tb_egpu_lever_m_fires)
  before adding the action mechanism in Commit 3.

Lifecycle change:
  tb_egpu_lever_m_recover_init() moved from end of nv_pci_probe to
  immediately after nvl->pci_dev assignment, so the WPR2 check has
  lever_m available. nv_pci_remove_helper teardown call is unchanged.

Builds on patch 0016 (Commit 1). Module params, sysfs counters, and
struct layout are unchanged.

Bumps version 595.71.05-aorus.6 → aorus.7.

Tasks: #62
---
diff --git a/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.c b/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.c
index 286e7510..1000ae98 100644
--- a/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.c
+++ b/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.c
@@ -52,6 +52,16 @@
 #include <linux/sysfs.h>
 #include <linux/slab.h>
 #include <linux/device.h>
+#include <linux/io.h>      /* ioremap, ioread32, iounmap */
+#include <linux/types.h>
+
+/* WPR2 status register: NV_HUBMMU0_PRI_BASE + NV_HUBMMU_PRI_MMU_WPR2_ADDR_HI
+ * for Blackwell GB100/GB202 (per published headers
+ * src/common/inc/swref/published/blackwell/gb100/{hwproject.h,
+ * dev_hubmmu_base.h}). DRF field _VAL is bits [31:4]; non-zero means
+ * WPR2 is up. */
+#define TB_EGPU_LEVER_M_WPR2_REG_OFFSET   0x88a828u
+#define TB_EGPU_LEVER_M_WPR2_VAL_MASK     0xfffffff0u    /* bits 31:4 */
 
 /* Module parameters — kill switch + tunables. Default-on so the lever
  * is engaged by default once landed; revert path is to set
@@ -162,6 +172,84 @@ static DEVICE_ATTR(tb_egpu_lever_m_surrenders, 0444,
 static DEVICE_ATTR(tb_egpu_lever_m_last_fire_jiffies, 0444,
                    tb_egpu_lever_m_last_fire_jiffies_show, NULL);
 
+/* Commit 2: probe-time WPR2-stuck detection.
+ *
+ * Reads the GSP MMU WPR2 status register via a temporary ioremap of a
+ * single page covering the register offset. We can't use nv->regs->map
+ * because at this point in nv_pci_probe (before RM init), NVIDIA's RM
+ * code hasn't yet ioremapped BAR0. Our own ioremap is safe and
+ * exclusive — we map for the duration of the read, then iounmap.
+ *
+ * Detection-only in this commit. No recovery action; probe continues.
+ * Increments lever_m->fire_count to track real-world rate.
+ */
+bool tb_egpu_lever_m_check_wpr2_at_probe(nv_linux_state_t *nvl,
+                                        u64 bar0_phys_addr)
+{
+    nv_state_t  *nv;
+    void __iomem *tmp_map;
+    u64          page_aligned_phys;
+    u32          page_offset;
+    u32          wpr2_raw;
+    u32          wpr2_val;
+
+    if (!nvl)
+        return false;
+
+    if (!NVreg_TbEgpuLeverMRecoverEnable || !nvl->lever_m)
+    {
+        /* Lever disabled or per-pdev state not allocated; nothing to do. */
+        return false;
+    }
+
+    nv = NV_STATE_PTR(nvl);
+
+    /* Page-align the mapping. We only need to read 4 bytes at offset
+     * 0x88a828, but ioremap must operate on page boundaries. */
+    page_aligned_phys = (bar0_phys_addr + TB_EGPU_LEVER_M_WPR2_REG_OFFSET) & PAGE_MASK;
+    page_offset       = (bar0_phys_addr + TB_EGPU_LEVER_M_WPR2_REG_OFFSET) & ~PAGE_MASK;
+
+    tmp_map = ioremap(page_aligned_phys, PAGE_SIZE);
+    if (!tmp_map)
+    {
+        NV_DEV_PRINTF(NV_DBG_INFO, nv,
+            "AORUS Lever M-recover: WPR2 detection — ioremap failed at probe; "
+            "skipping check (probe continues normally)\n");
+        return false;
+    }
+
+    wpr2_raw = ioread32(tmp_map + page_offset);
+    iounmap(tmp_map);
+
+    wpr2_val = wpr2_raw & TB_EGPU_LEVER_M_WPR2_VAL_MASK;
+
+    if (wpr2_val == 0)
+    {
+        NV_DEV_PRINTF(NV_DBG_INFO, nv,
+            "AORUS Lever M-recover: WPR2 check at probe — clear (raw=0x%08x); "
+            "GSP boot should proceed normally\n", wpr2_raw);
+        return false;
+    }
+
+    /* WPR2 is up. Increment counter and log marker. Recovery action is
+     * deferred to Commit 3 — for now, probe continues; the existing
+     * failure path (rm_init_adapter fails on first nv_start_device,
+     * aorus-egpu-wpr2-recovery.service performs L4 recovery) is
+     * unchanged. */
+    atomic_inc(&nvl->lever_m->fire_count);
+    nvl->lever_m->last_fire_jiffies = jiffies;
+
+    NV_DEV_PRINTF(NV_DBG_ERRORS, nv,
+        "AORUS Lever M-recover: WPR2 DETECTED UP at probe (raw=0x%08x val=0x%08x). "
+        "Commit 2 detection only — recovery action pending Commit 3. "
+        "L4 helper (aorus-egpu-wpr2-recovery.service) will handle recovery via "
+        "the existing dmesg-pattern-detection path. fire_count=%d\n",
+        wpr2_raw, wpr2_val,
+        atomic_read(&nvl->lever_m->fire_count));
+
+    return true;
+}
+
 int tb_egpu_lever_m_recover_init(nv_linux_state_t *nvl)
 {
     struct tb_egpu_lever_m_recover *lm;
diff --git a/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.h b/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.h
index e1771073..cf14bab9 100644
--- a/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.h
+++ b/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.h
@@ -59,4 +59,34 @@ struct tb_egpu_lever_m_recover
 int  tb_egpu_lever_m_recover_init(nv_linux_state_t *nvl);
 void tb_egpu_lever_m_recover_stop(nv_linux_state_t *nvl);
 
+/* Probe-time WPR2-stuck detection (Commit 2 of patch 0016).
+ *
+ * Reads the GSP MMU WPR2 status register at BAR0 + 0x88a828
+ * (NV_HUBMMU0_PRI_BASE + NV_HUBMMU_PRI_MMU_WPR2_ADDR_HI on Blackwell
+ * GB100/GB202). If bits [31:4] are non-zero, WPR2 is stuck up from a
+ * previous boot cycle and GSP boot will fail (see H13 in
+ * docs/reliability-hypothesis-ledger.md).
+ *
+ * Detection-only in this commit — increments lever_m->fire_count and
+ * logs a marker. No recovery action; probe continues normally. The
+ * existing failure path (rm_init_adapter returns error in nv_start_device,
+ * L4 helper aorus-egpu-wpr2-recovery.service does the recovery) is
+ * unchanged. Provides real-world fire rate via sysfs counter.
+ *
+ * Commit 3 will replace the no-op recovery action with pci-level
+ * remove + rescan + reset, eliminating the userspace race per
+ * docs/lever-M-recover-design.md.
+ *
+ * Caller must pass the BAR0 physical address (from nv->bars[REGS]).
+ * Function does its own temporary ioremap+iounmap; safe to call any
+ * time after pci_enable_device has succeeded and the BAR address is
+ * known. Cheap (~1 register read).
+ *
+ * Returns: NV_TRUE if WPR2 detected up, NV_FALSE if clear or any other
+ *          error (e.g. ioremap failed). Either way, probe should
+ *          continue — return value is informational.
+ */
+bool tb_egpu_lever_m_check_wpr2_at_probe(nv_linux_state_t *nvl,
+                                        u64 bar0_phys_addr);
+
 #endif /* _NV_LEVER_M_RECOVER_H_ */
diff --git a/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-pci.c b/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-pci.c
index c0210ef5..95ad91fd 100644
--- a/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-pci.c
+++ b/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-pci.c
@@ -1918,6 +1918,23 @@ nv_pci_probe
     nvl->pci_dev           = pci_dev;
     nvl->dma_dev.dev       = nvl->dev;
 
+    /* AORUS Lever M-recover (Phase 4, 2026-05-06) Commit 2:
+     * Allocate per-pdev recovery state EARLY (was at end of probe in
+     * Commit 1) so it's available for the WPR2 check below. Failure
+     * is non-fatal — leaves nvl->lever_m=NULL; check short-circuits. */
+    (void)tb_egpu_lever_m_recover_init(nvl);
+
+    /* AORUS Lever M-recover Commit 2: probe-time WPR2-stuck detection.
+     *
+     * Reads GSP MMU WPR2 status register (BAR0 + 0x88a828). If non-zero,
+     * WPR2 is stuck from a previous boot cycle; GSP boot will fail when
+     * nv_start_device subsequently calls rm_init_adapter. THIS COMMIT
+     * IS DETECTION-ONLY — increments fire_count and logs a marker, but
+     * probe continues. Existing L4 helper handles recovery. Commit 3
+     * will add in-driver pci_reset_bus action to retire the L4 helper. */
+    (void)tb_egpu_lever_m_check_wpr2_at_probe(nvl,
+        nv->bars[NV_GPU_BAR_INDEX_REGS].cpu_address);
+
     nv->pci_info.vendor_id = pci_dev->vendor;
     nv->pci_info.device_id = pci_dev->device;
     nv->subsystem_id       = pci_dev->subsystem_device;
@@ -2204,12 +2221,10 @@ nv_pci_probe
      * watchdog, falling back to the existing Q-active wrapper. */
     (void)tb_egpu_qwatchdog_init(nvl);
 
-    /* AORUS Lever M-recover (Phase 4, 2026-05-06): allocate per-pdev
-     * state for in-driver recovery. Commit 1 scaffolding only —
-     * struct + workqueue + sysfs counters. Behaviour change comes in
-     * commits 2 (probe-time WPR2 detection) and 3 (AER callback path).
-     * Failure non-fatal; driver continues without recovery state. */
-    (void)tb_egpu_lever_m_recover_init(nvl);
+    /* AORUS Lever M-recover init was moved earlier in probe (line ~1920)
+     * in Commit 2 so the WPR2 check has lever_m available; no longer
+     * called here. Stop is still called at the corresponding teardown
+     * point in nv_pci_remove_helper. */
 
     nv_kmem_cache_free_stack(sp);
 
